{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517843"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:57:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12840"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12840"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.01,0.06,0.67,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52016"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5283"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12840"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37325"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"356"},{"type":"tags","id":"1147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1894"},{"type":"tags","id":"2437"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52016"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 83-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with ongoing urinary problems that have persisted for a long time. He describes increased urgency and incomplete emptying of his bladder. He gets up once or twice at night to void. He has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. There is no family history of prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A prior ultrasound of the urinary tract showed an enlarged central gland which is hypoechoic, bladder wall hypertrophy, and a large prostate with a volume of 55 cc. His post-void residual volume was 275 mL. His current PSA is 2.4 ng/mL (0-4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient was diagnosed with benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) six months ago and was initially commenced on tamsulosin. He has returned to the clinic because there has been minimal improvement in his urinary symptoms despite treatment. You inform the patient that additional treatments may have potential for significant side effects of lowering active testosterone and causing erectile dysfunction and loss of libido. However, the patient states that he is a widower for 10 years and has no plans on finding a new partner; he would be willing to have the treatment despite the potential for side effects because of how much the urinary issues are impacting his quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase the dose of tamsulosin","Persist with current medication","Change to dutasteride","Prescribe a dutasteride/tamsulosin combination","Trans-urethral resection of prostate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic urinary retention most likely due to an enlarged prostate (benign prostatic hyperplasia, BPH). The patient\u0027s symptomatology and PSA level (less than 3 ng/mL) make prostate cancer unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing a combination of dutasteride/tamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate medical management to improve the patient\u0027s urinary retention. This combination helps reduce prostate size and improve urinary retention symptoms, and is significantly more effective than tamsulosin monotherapy. There are major potential side effects with dutasteride, particularly lower levels of testosterone resulting in loss of libido and erectile dysfunction. However, the patient has stated that he is willing to accept these potential side effects if they will help resolve his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersisting with current medication\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best choice as the treatment has minimally helped with symptoms, and some change in treatment seems needed. Tamsulosin, a selective \u237a-1A and \u237a-1B adrenoceptor antagonist, can improve urinary flow by relaxing the smooth muscle in the bladder and prostate. It is often a first-line treatment in chronic urinary retention. However, as it has not been effective for this patient, a change in management is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease the dose of tamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. The drug typically has its largest impacts within four to six weeks, and increasing the dose is unlikely to provide significant additional benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging to dutasteride\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not appropriate. Dutasteride is a 5\u03b1-reductase inhibitor that must be prescribed with an alpha-blocker under PBS listing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrans-urethral resection of prostate (TURP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate surgical intervention to help reduce the size of the prostate and improve the patient\u0027s current symptoms. However, it is not the first line of management, and all medical treatments should be tried first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, given the patient\u0027s large prostate size (55 cc), persistent symptoms despite tamsulosin monotherapy, and willingness to accept potential side effects, a combination of dutasteride and tamsulosin (such as DuoDart) is the most appropriate next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with a large prostate (above 50 cc) may be prescribed dutasteride for BPH, but there are major potential side effects such as erectile dysfunction and loss of libido.","A combination of dutasteride and tamsulosin is used in BPH to treat urinary retention when tamsulosin monotherapy is ineffective."],"references":["Marihart S, Harik M, Djavan B. Dutasteride: a review of current data on a novel dual inhibitor of 5alpha reductase. Rev Urol. 2005;7(4):203-10. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1550785/","Ng M, Baradhi KM. Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK558920/","Kim EH, Larson JA, Andriole GL. Management of Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia. Annu Rev Med. 2016;67:137-51. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26331999/","Ballstaedt L, Leslie SW, Woodbury B. Bladder Post Void Residual Volume. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2024 Feb 28. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539839/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37325"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12840"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37325"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-01T20:03:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-01T20:05:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5283"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52016"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"descrip